english:
  title: Six Songs of Dongfeng
  author: Kim Si-seup
  language: eng
  text: |-
    There is a visitor, a visitor called Dongfeng.
    White hair tangled like dragon whiskers, bent with age.
    Before reaching manhood, I studied both brush and blade,
    Scorning the meager countenance of a pedantic scholar.

    One dawn, my household scattered like clouds dispersing,
    Caught in currents with none to follow my path.
    Ah, I sing the first song, and it sounds only of sorrow:
    The vast sky stretches empty, knowing nothing.
    The thorned branches jut forth with countless barbs,
    Grasping and stumbling, I wander all four directions.
    North to the Khitans, south to the distant lands—
    Where can I bury this ache within my breast?
    Daylight fades, the road stretches endlessly before me,
    How can I mount the roc and soar ninety thousand leagues?

    Ah, I sing the second song with measured cadence:
    The north wind blows desolation for my sake.
    My grandfather loved me when I was small,
    Delighting in my reading on each passing month.
    My learning grew straight and true; he taught me text and numbers,
    Seven-character verses flowing with grace.
    The Honorable Emperor heard and summoned me to the crimson hall,
    One stroke of the great brush, and dragons soared.
    Ah, I sing the third song, and it moves slowly:
    Ambitions unfulfilled, my life's course overturned.

    My mother, of the Mencius clan,
    Raised me with tender care through three migrations of home,
    Saying, "Learn the way of the Sage King,
    That you might restore the virtues of ancient Tang."
    Yet who knew that this very name would become my undoing?
    Ten years I have wandered the mountain roads in haste.
    Ah, I sing the fourth song, and it chokes with sorrow:
    The filial crow returns to feed its mother in the valley.
    The azure sky swept clean of clouds above,
    The bitter wind whistles through the withered grass.
    I stand in my despair gazing at the heavens—
    If I am but a grain of rice, why does heaven grow old?
    Why was I born to this loneliness, this unique suffering?
    My heart finds kinship with none among the multitude.

    Ah, I sing the fifth song, and it tears the very heartstrings:
    O spirit, return to me from all the world's far corners!
    I grasp my bow, determined to shoot at Sirius,
    While Tai-yi holds station at the center of heaven.
    I finger my long sword, ready to strike down the great fox,
    As the white tiger lurks at the mountain's edge.
    But my ardent heart remains unvoiced,
    And I whistle long into the empty air alone.

    Ah, I sing the sixth song, and it is suffused with sighs:
    My noble aspirations lie broken and scattered,
    And I can only stroke my beard in futility.
  footnotes:
    - Dongfeng (東峰) is the author's own name or epithet, meaning 'Eastern Peak,' suggesting both a place of retreat and spiritual elevation.
    - The six songs form a spiritual autobiography, tracing the speaker's trajectory from youthful promise through disillusionment to final resignation.
    - References to Khitans (韎羯) and distant lands reflect the author's actual wanderings and exile.
    - The Mencius clan (孟氏) alludes to a noble lineage, while Mencius himself exemplifies virtue and learning.
    - Sirius (天狼), the white tiger, and other celestial imagery represent both cosmic order and the author's thwarted ambitions to restore virtue to the realm.
    - The roc (붕새) represents impossible transcendence, while the grain of rice symbolizes insignificance despite one's worth.
